    "question_id" : 4355303,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>I Also Faced This Problem.\nTo Solve This I have first converted my long to String then to int.</p>\n<pre><code>int i = Integer.parseInt(String.valueOf(long));\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 20879788,
      "reputation" : 41,
      "user_id" : 15337823,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/AOh14GhPC634H8ebLaBWHa8xcEyXTiy-zl1LkA2odiiLHw=k-s256",
      "display_name" : "Daniel Tam",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/15337823/daniel-tam"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 0,
    "last_activity_date" : 1615412515,
    "creation_date" : 1615412515,
    "answer_id" : 66573283,
    "question_id" : 4355303,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<pre><code>long x;\nint y;\ny = (int) x\n</code></pre>\n<p>You can cast a long to int so long as the number is less than 2147483647 without an error.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 9901847,
      "reputation" : 79,
      "user_id" : 7331630,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/9ce9501554c4779615e3d8eca5d0602a?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "ryuik",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/7331630/ryuik"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 0,
    "last_activity_date" : 1632856412,
    "last_edit_date" : 1632856412,
    "creation_date" : 1632849032,
    "answer_id" : 69365904,
    "question_id" : 4355303,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>I'm adding few key details.</p>\n<p>Basically what Java does is truncate <code>long</code> after 32 bits, so simple typecasting will do the trick:</p>\n<pre><code>    long l=100000000000000000l;\n    System.out.println(Long.toString(l,2));\n    int t=(int)l;\n    System.out.println(Integer.toString(t,2));\n</code></pre>\n<p>Which outputs:</p>\n<pre><code>101100011010001010111100001011101100010100000000000000000\n                          1011101100010100000000000000000\n</code></pre>\n<p>for <code>l=1000000043634760000l</code> it outputs:</p>\n<pre><code>110111100000101101101011110111010000001110011001100101000000\n                             -101111110001100110011011000000\n</code></pre>\n<p>If we convert this <code>-101111110001100110011011000000</code> in proper two's compliment we will get the exact 32-bit signed truncated from the <code>long</code>.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 27178441,
      "reputation" : 1,
      "user_id" : 20714092,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/xFfUgzci.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Senim Kesharwani",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/20714092/senim-kesharwani"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 0,
    "last_activity_date" : 1672777144,
    "last_edit_date" : 1672777144,
    "creation_date" : 1672769477,
    "answer_id" : 74997134,
    "question_id" : 4355303,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<pre class=\"lang-java prettyprint-override\"><code>// Java Program to convert long to int\n  \nclass Main {\n  public static void main(String[] args) {\n  \n    // create long variable\n    long value1 = 523386L;\n    long value2 = -4456368L;\n  \n    // change long to int\n    int num1 = Math.toIntExact(value1);\n    int num2 = Math.toIntExact(value2);\n      \n    // print the type\n    System.out.println(&quot;Converted type: &quot;+ ((Object)num1).getClass().getName());\n    System.out.println(&quot;Converted type: &quot;+ ((Object)num2).getClass().getName());\n  \n    // print the int value\n    System.out.println(num1);  // 52336\n    System.out.println(num2);  // -445636\n  }\n}\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 30153205,
      "reputation" : 11,
      "user_id" : 23108123,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/t9wJq.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "bladeart0-0",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/23108123/bladeart0-0"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 0,
    "last_activity_date" : 1702659514,
    "creation_date" : 1702659514,
    "answer_id" : 77667741,
    "question_id" : 4355303,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>You should be able to directly narrowly typecast/cast up from the higher data type (the long) to the lower one (the int), which would look like:</p>\n<pre><code>    long x = 101010101L;\n\n    //explicit type casting\n    int y=(int)x; \n</code></pre>\n<p>Note that there would be some issues with a loss of data due to the smaller range of values accepted by the int.</p>\n<pre><code>    long l = 2147483648L;\n\n    // \n    // T\n    // And we are trying to store a value in i \n    // greater than its upper limit\n    int i = (int) l;\n</code></pre>\n<p>(prints as -2147483648)</p>\n<p>This would not be an issue with your example value. You can do this because both types of data are primitive values; whereas, if you were converting a string to an integer you would not be able to do this due to the string contents including characters, which are not accepted values for integers.</p>\n<p>You would also be able to engage in explicit type conversion, which is used when converting the value of one data type to another data type without the compiler being able to do so. This would look like</p>\n<pre><code>    //returns argument as int\n    //will throw ArithmaticException if the result overflows the int\n    //aka it is out of the range of -2,147,483,648 to 2,147,483,647\n    int b=Math.toIntExact(x);\n\n    int c= x.IntValue();\n</code></pre>\n<p>Note how this throws an exception when the long is out of range to be stored as an int rather than engaging in wraparound behavior and counting up from the negative limit of int after exceeding the maximum value of int.</p>\n<p>When choosing between type casting or type conversion, you should note that casting changes the type of the variable, while conversion changes the representation or format of the value. Casting converts between compatible data types, while conversion can convert incompatible data types as well. Casting can result in data loss or truncation with narrowing (as in your case), while conversion can involve the manipulation or changing of data without changing the data type.</p>\n<p>You can also reference here for more information:</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.scaler.com/topics/java/type-casting-in-java/\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">https://www.scaler.com/topics/java/type-casting-in-java/</a></p>\n"
  } ],
